Project Information

Project Team: PTID-CDS-DEC-25-3482

Project Name: PRCP-1002 Handwritten Digits Recognition

Problem Statement

Handwritten digit recognition is a fundamental problem in the field of computer vision and machine learning.
The objective of this project is to build a system that can accurately classify a given image of a handwritten digit into one of the 10 classes representing digits from 0 to 9.

This project uses the MNIST dataset, which is a standard benchmark dataset widely used for evaluating classification algorithms. The dataset consists of grayscale images of handwritten digits and provides a strong foundation to experiment with different machine learning and deep learning techniques.

Project Objectives

The main objectives of this project are:

  • To perform a complete exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the MNIST dataset
  • To build classification models capable of recognizing handwritten digits
  • To compare multiple models and analyze their performance
  • To identify the best-performing model suitable for production use

Dataset Description

The dataset used in this project is the MNIST (Modified National Institute of Standards and Technology) dataset.

Dataset Characteristics:

  • The dataset contains tens of thousands of grayscale images
  • Each image represents a single handwritten digit
  • Image dimensions are 28 28 pixels
  • Pixel values range from 0 to 255
  • The output consists of 10 classes, representing digits from 0 to 9

The dataset is well-structured and labeled, making it suitable for both traditional machine learning algorithms and deep learning-based approaches.

Skills and Techniques Covered

Through this project, the following skills and techniques are practiced:

  • Computer vision fundamentals
  • Image preprocessing and normalization
  • Classification techniques such as:
    • Logistic Regression
    • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
    • Support Vector Machines (SVM)
    • Artificial Neural Networks (ANN)
    • Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN)
  • Model evaluation and performance comparison

Project Workflow

The overall workflow of the project is structured as follows:

  1. Dataset loading and understanding
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  3. Data preprocessing and normalization
  4. Building multiple classification models
  5. Model evaluation and comparison
  6. Selection of the best model for production
  7. Discussion of challenges faced and solutions applied

Note

All the above tasks are implemented within a single Jupyter Notebook, as required.
The complete workflow is documented using code cells, visualizations, and explanatory markdown cells.

from tensorflow.keras.datasets import mnist
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Load the data
(x_train, y_train), (_, _) = mnist.load_data()

# Flatten 28x28 images to 1D vectors (784 features)
x_flat = x_train.reshape(x_train.shape[0], -1)

# Optional: Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]
x_flat = x_flat / 255.0

# Standardize data (important for PCA)
scaler = StandardScaler()
x_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(x_flat)

# Apply PCA to reduce to 2 components
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
x_pca = pca.fit_transform(x_scaled)

# Convert to DataFrame for plotting
df_pca = pd.DataFrame(data=x_pca, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'])
df_pca['label'] = y_train

# Plot the PCA result
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.scatterplot(x='PC1', y='PC2', hue='label', data=df_pca, palette='tab10', alpha=0.6, s=15)
plt.title("MNIST Visualization using PCA (2 Components)")
plt.legend(title='Digit', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In[20]:
# Check how much variance is retained
pca_full = PCA().fit(x_scaled)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_[:50]), marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.title('Variance Explained by PCA Components')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

a = accuracy_score # evaluation metrics for classification model
p = precision_score
f = f1_score
def evaluate_model(true, predicted):
    accuracy_score = a(true, predicted) # evaluation metrics for classification model
    precision_score = p(true, predicted)
    f1_score_score = f(true, predicted)
    return accuracy_score,precision_score,f1_score_score # evaluation metrics for classification model

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
In[27]:
# Flatten the 28x28 images to 784-dimension vectors
X_train_flat = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0], -1)
X_test_flat = X_test.reshape(X_test.shape[0], -1)

# Normalize pixel values [0, 1]
X_train_flat = X_train_flat / 255.0
X_test_flat = X_test_flat / 255.0

# Optional: Reduce to smaller set to prevent MemoryError
X = np.concatenate((X_train_flat, X_test_flat), axis=0)
y = np.concatenate((y_train, y_test), axis=0)

X_sub, _, y_sub, _ = train_test_split(X, y, train_size=2000, stratify=y, random_state=42)  # Use only 2000 samples

# Split into train/test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_sub, y_sub, test_size=0.25, stratify=y_sub, random_state=42)

# Standardize
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Define models
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    "K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)": KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "Random Forest Classifier": RandomForestClassifier(),
    "Support Vector Machine": SVC(),
    "Gradient Boosting Classifier": GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    "MLPClassifier": MLPClassifier(max_iter=500)
}
In[29]:
# Evaluate models
model_list=[]
accuracy_score_list =[]
for i in range(len(list(models))):
    model = list(models.values())[i]
    # Use scaled data where required
    if model in ["Logistic Regression", "Support Vector Machine", "MLPClassifier"]:
        model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
        y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train_scaled)
        y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

    else:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
        y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    model_list.append(list(models.keys())[i])



# Training metrics
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    train_prec = precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train, average='macro', zero_division=0)
    train_f1 = f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train, average='macro')

    # Test metrics
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    test_prec = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test, average='macro', zero_division=0)
    test_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test, average='macro')

    # Print formatted result
    print(f"\n{model}")
    print("Model Performance for Training set")
    print(f"- accuracy_score: {train_acc:.4f}")
    print(f"- precision_score: {train_prec:.4f}")
    print(f"- f1_score_score: {train_f1:.4f}")
    print("----------------------------------")
    print("Model performance for Test set")
    print(f"- accuracy_score: {test_acc:.4f}")
    print(f"- precision_score: {test_prec:.4f}")
    print(f"- f1_score_score: {test_f1:.4f}")
    print("===================================")

    accuracy_score_list.append(test_acc) # evaluation metrics for classification model

from sklearn.datasets import fetch_openml
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import time

# Load MNIST (only 5000 samples for speed)
X, y = fetch_openml('mnist_784', version=1, return_X_y=True, as_frame=False)
X, y = X[:5000], y[:5000]  # reduce for speed

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Define smaller parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'C': [1, 10],
    'kernel': ['linear', 'rbf']
}

# GridSearchCV
grid = GridSearchCV(SVC(), param_grid, cv=3, verbose=1, n_jobs=1)

# Fit and time
start = time.time()
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
end = time.time()

# Evaluation
print("Best Parameters:", grid.best_params_)

import tensorflow
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from tensorflow.keras.datasets import mnist
import time

# Load and preprocess MNIST data
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = mnist.load_data()
x_train = x_train.reshape(-1, 28*28) / 255.0
x_test = x_test.reshape(-1, 28*28) / 255.0

# Optional: reduce for speed
x_train_small = x_train[:5000]
y_train_small = y_train[:5000]

# Define parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100],
    'max_depth': [10, 20],
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy']
}

# Grid search
rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
grid1 = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid, cv=3, verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit
start = time.time()
grid1.fit(x_train_small, y_train_small)
end = time.time()

# Predict on test set
best_model = grid1.best_estimator_
y_pred_test = best_model.predict(x_test)

# Evaluation
print("Best Parameters:", grid1.best_params_)
print("Test Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test))

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from tensorflow.keras.datasets import mnist
import time

# Load MNIST data
(x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test) = mnist.load_data()

# Flatten and normalize
x_train = x_train.reshape(-1, 28*28) / 255.0
x_test = x_test.reshape(-1, 28*28) / 255.0

# Optional: Reduce training size for speed (KNN is slow)
x_train_small = x_train[:5000]
y_train_small = y_train[:5000]

# Define parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_neighbors': [3, 5, 7],
    'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'],
    'algorithm': ['auto']
}

# Initialize model and GridSearchCV
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
grid = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=3, verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit model
start = time.time()
grid.fit(x_train_small, y_train_small)
end = time.time()

# Best model and prediction
best_model = grid.best_estimator_
y_pred_test = best_model.predict(x_test)

# Evaluation
print("Best Parameters:", grid.best_params_)
print("Test Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test))

Model Comparison Report MNIST Dataset

Algorithms Used

I have used a total of machine learning algorithms to classify handwritten digits from the MNIST dataset:

  • Logistic Regression
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
  • Random Forest
  • Gradient Boosting
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM)
  • MLPClassifier

Best Performing Models

  • The following models showed superior performance on the MNIST dataset:
    • Support Vector Machine (SVM) Accuracy: ~92%
    • MLPClassifier Accuracy: ~90%
    • K-Nearest Neighbors Accuracy: ~90%
    • Random Forest Accuracy: ~91%

Moderate Performing Models

  • Models showing moderate performance:
    • Logistic Regression ~86%
    • Gradient Boosting ~89%

Final Challenges and Observations

Data Normalization

  • MNIST images have pixel values ranging from 0 to 255.
  • Scaling to 01 range improves model accuracy, especially for algorithms like SVM and KNN.

Feature Representation

  • All 784 pixel features are numerical and flattened from 2828 images.
  • CNNs can better capture spatial structure of images.

Model Tuning

  • Hyperparameter tuning is critical for models like MLP, XGBoost, and SVM.
  • Techniques like GridSearchCV or RandomizedSearchCV improve performance.
